1. Introduction to the central research objective

Europe emitted 1092.345 of Mt CO2 in 2022, in which two big influential factors in the energy-related CO2 emissions are the Electricity and Heat Production (20% of total energy-related CO2 emissions) and Transport (43% of energy-related CO2 emissions). Moreover, it is also possible to analyze the emissions of different European countries, where it is noticed that the Netherlands is currently the eighth country in Europe per emissions.

Given the significant impact that transportation has in Europe and, consequently, in the Netherlands, the government has tried to introduce several environmental policies to encourage the citizens to adopt more sustainable forms of transportation.

Having that in mind, the central research question guiding this investigation is: How have European environmental policies influenced the adoption of sustainable transportation methods in major Dutch cities over the past ten years?

To address this question comprehensively, we will explore three subquestions that delve into specific policy impacts:

  1. How do Dutch tax incentives impact the increase in electric vehicle registrations?

    This subquestion regards the impact of European policies on the electric vehicle (EV) subsidies. Our analysis aims to examine the differences before and after the introduction of the financial incentives by the European Commission and the Dutch Government. The impact of such policies is studied by conducting a quantitative analysis to show the change in mobility usage.

  2. To what extent have investments in cycling infrastructure impacted the use of bicycles as a daily means of transport?

    This subquestion aims to map new cycling infrastructure and correlate it with bicycle traffic figures. Comparative analyses among cities with varying levels of investment will provide insights into how those can influence cycling habits. This can be done by utilizing geospacial visualizations, illustrating the development of cycling networks and their impact on daily commuting patterns.

  3. How have emission restriction policies (e.g. Euro standards) changed public transportation usage, in accordance to meeting the European emission goals?

    This subquestion focuses on quantifying the changes and the effectiveness of those policies in private, public and commercial transportation, by comparing the transport-related CO2 emissions before and after the implementation of those policies. We will, therefore, estimate the long-term environmental impacts using comparative analysis.

2. Policies to stimulate Electic Vehicle sales

The Netherlands government has implemented various incentives, which were put into place on July 2020, in order to boost new Electric Vehicle (EV) sales, as a primary option to drastically reduce greenhouse gases emissions (namely CO2). Incentives are categorized into subsidies and tax exemptions. A brief overview of the maximum subsidies is shown below:

  • Used EV car subsidy (for private owners): 2000 Euros
  • New EV car subsidy (for private owners): 2950 Euros
  • New EV car subsidy (for company fleets): 5000 Euros

As far as tax exemptions and reductions are concerned, these are implemented into two tax types: Purchase tax (BPM) and ownership tax (MRB). These are summarized below:

  • For BPM:
    • Full exemption until the end of 2024
    • Discount of 360 Euros per car for 2025
    • Discounted, but gradually increasing BPM for 2026 and onwards
  • For MRB:
    • Full exemtion until the end of 2024
    • 75% discount for 2025
    • 50% discount for 2026 and onwards

For the purposes of this study, we will focus on the 8-year period between 2016 and 2024, which is split into two particular periods: Pre-incentive period (2016-2020) and post-incentive period (2020-2024). Subsequently, comparisons between those two will be conducted.

2.1 Total number of passenger vehicles registered in the Netherlands between 2016 and 2024

Firstly, the total number of passenger cars is presented in relation to the number of EVs.

As it is seen from the graph above, EVs accounted for only 1% of the Netherlands' passenger vehicle fleet in 2016, while this percentage rose to 7% in 2024. Currently, it is estimated that 636.700 EVs are in the Dutch roads. Moreover, the gradient of the EV number curve is noticeably higher on and after 2020, where those particular incentives where established.

This figure shows the year-on-year growth of the passenger fleet in the Netherlands, in relation with that of the EVs. While the overall growth of the fleet has remained in the same levels over the examined period (0.86% to 1.83%), EVs experienced an increase that fluctuated between 8.87% to 42.5%, with an average value of 28.85%. Also, a spike is observed on the year-on-year growth between 2019 and 2020, while the levels of it have not fallen below 29% until 2024. So, it is safe to say that government subsidies have helped boost electic vehicle sales on a respectable level.

2.3 Price of new EVs

According to this graph, average prices of new EVs were in a steady decline throughout the examined period. Specifically, prices decreased from 68000 Euros in 2016 to about 61000 Euros in 2024. This, combined with the potential 2950 Euro subsidy, creates fairly favourable conditions for new buyers.

As we can see from the analysis above, average prices of new EVs have fallen by almost 11% during the examined period. Meanwhile, an 8-fold increase on electric vehicle sales is observed, while the year-on-year growth of EV sales is significantly larger throughout the 8-year period. This implies that the market share of EVs will take an increasing stake in the vehicle market if this trend continues. A contributing factor to that, are the Dutch government incentives, which undoubtedly help stimulate electric vehicle demand, as it is illustrated by the significant difference between the year-on-year growth of sales between pre and post-incentive period. Nevertheless, during upcoming years, those subsidies will depleat to some extend, so it would be interesting to examine market's behaviour during the upcoming years. This could be a future research material.

3. Investment in cycling infrastructure related to the increase in daily cycling use

Investments in cycling infrastructure in the Netherlands have been basic to ensuring that bicycles become a common means of daily transportation. Some of the investments have caused less congestion in traffic, reduced carbon emissions, and promoted healthier lifestyles for the Dutch people. Starting in the 1970s, as a response to the oil crisis and growing concern over road safety, the Dutch government initiated huge investments in cycling infrastructure (BBC News, 2013). This meant constructing thorough networks of separated bike facilities as well as designing traffic-calmed neighborhoods, or "woonerfs." The following decades of established funding expanded these networks, integrated bike routes with public transport, and added amenities such as guarded bike parking and priority-to-cyclists traffic lights. Many trips in ther biggest cities in the Netherlands like Amsterdam and Utrecht are now reported to be taken by bicycle. The sustained commitment to the improvement of cycling infrastructure, supported by national policies and awareness in the public, is demonstrated through a huge increase in the daily use of bicycles within the country. The following graphs show the relation between these investments and increased bicycle traffic in various cities in the Netherlands.

BBC News. (2013, August 7). Why is cycling so popular in the Netherlands? https://www.bbc.com/news/magazine-23587916

3.1 Trends in Bicycle Usage by Category in the Netherlands (2015-2022)

The graph above shows the trend in the number of bicycles sold in the Netherlands from 2015 to 2022 by type. In the graph, sales are divided into the following classes: City Bicycles, Electric Bicycles,Children's Bicycles, Hybrid Bicycles (including tracking bicycles),Other Bicycles (which include racing and mountain bikes) and the number of Total Bicycles sold each year. The graph below is an animated bar chart that represents a yearly comparison. This is to dynamically show how the sales of bicycles have varied over time. In this graph, each category of the bicycle is differentiated by the use of different colors for each type. Therefore, it is very clear which is which. This graph shows horizontal bars that depict a number of bicycles sold for each category. The animation moves from 2015 through 2022, and there are several key trends to identify. As far as Electric Bicycles are concerned, sales have grown remarkably over these years. This can be pinpointed to increased acceptance of electric mobility solutions, advances in technology, rising environmental awareness, and favorable government policies for green transport. As far as City Bicycles go, sales are relatively stable. This signifies that the bicycle remains of primary importance for urban transportation in the Netherlands. This consistency in the sales figures is indicative of the deeply entrenched cycling culture and infrastructure of the country. Thirdly, other bicycle types, such as Hybrid Bicycles, Children's Bicycles, and Other Bicycles (racing and mountain bikes), have minor fluctuations but generally keep steady trends. These may perhaps be attributed to factors that influence consumer preference and recreational trends, which again are determined by the demographic aspect. In general, the Total Bicycles sold annually show the popularity of cycling in the Netherlands. The increased total sales further develop the hypothesis that investment in cycling infrastructure increases bicycle usage for daily transportation. Some striking trends in bicycle sales, from 2015 to 2022, as can be seen in the graph, are a sharp increase in the sale of electric bicycles on one hand and continued popularity regarding city bicycles. These findings give some insight into changing consumer preferences and the results of infrastructure investments in cycling behavior in the Netherlands.

3.2 Regional Investment Trends in Infrastructure (2009-2022) and Relative Distribution of Cycle Network Length by Region in 2024

The first graph illustrates the investment in cycling infrastructure by region in the Netherlands each year from 2010 to 2022, where in general the most noticeable trend is the sharp increase in investment after 2020, reaching more than EUR 30 million by 2022. This surge indicates a renewed focus on cycling infrastructure, probably driven by recent policy initiatives to promote sustainable urban mobility. The trend for Zuid-Nederland remained mostly flat from 2010 to 2018, with investments close to zero, until 2020 where there is a significant increase, peaking at just over EUR 10 million by 2022. Oost-Nederland shows a more fluctuating trend. There is a peak around 2014, where investments briefly jumped to around EUR 5 million, followed by a rapid decline, with another minor peak around 2018, but overall investments remain lower than in the other regions. Noord-Nederland shows the most consistent but low investment levels, with only small peaks, particularly around 2010 and 2020, never exceeding EUR 5 million. The second graph represents the share of cycling network length across various regions in the year 2024: West-Nederland with 32.5%, Oost-Nederland with 27.4%, and Zuid-Nederland with 23.9%. With the lowest share, Noord-Nederland only occupies 16.3%, which leaves more room for development in the future. These graphs provide insight into how invested funds relate to infrastructure coverage, emphasizing that financial priorities within these main regions are given to extending the cycling network.

3.3 Comparative Analysis of Regional Investments and Average Kilometers Biked per Person (2009-2022)

The coloured bars represent the annual investments in cycling infrastructure for each of the Dutch regions analysed above. Interestingly, the orange line shows the trend in average kilometres cycled per person per year and how this trend relates to the funds invested. Starting in 2017, a clear positive trend is observed, with a significant increase in kilometres travelled peaking at around 1100 km per person in 2022. It should be noted that this increase coincides with an intensification of investments, especially in the West-Nederland and Zuid-Nederland regions, suggesting a correlation between increased funding for infrastructure and increased cycling. Furthermore, it is conceivable that the decrease between 2009 and 2010 indicates a decrease in cycling activity, which could be related to various factors, such as unfavourable economic conditions or particularly bad weather conditions during that period.

3.4 Regional Bicycle Usage Trends per Region

This graph shows a very interesting trend in cycling that took place within the Dutch regions between 2018 and 2023, underlining the same dynamic of fall and recovery. Within the period of 2018 to 2020, all regions had been experiencing a decline in bicycle use that could be related to the pandemic and movement restrictions. But from 2021, upwards are a gradual recovery in 2022, with regions such as East and West Netherlands returning to similar or even higher levels than in 2018. This trend of recovery can almost be interpreted as an indication of increased popularity after the pandemic, due to both renewed interest in sustainable mobility and the desire to maintain social distancing and a healthier lifestyle. The fact that all regions follow this similar trend suggests the effectiveness of one uniform national policy of support for cycling infrastructure.

3.5 Trends in Bicycle Usage by Travel Motives in the Netherlands (2018-2023)

The graph illustrates how the motivations for cycling in the Netherlands have changed between 2018 and 2023. It can be clearly seen that the main reason for bicycle use is shopping and spending (light blue line), which maintained a high level, fluctuating slightly in 2021 probably due to the COVID-19 restrictions, but with a stable recovery in 2022 and 2023, in fact this suggests that, even during lockdown periods, cycling remained a popular means of shopping locally. The second most common reason is outings, sports and hobbies (dark green line), which declined sharply in 2020, probably due to restrictions on sports and recreational activities during the pandemic. However, this category like the previous one showed a strong recovery in 2022, indicating a return to outdoor and recreational activities as soon as restrictions were relaxed. In contrast, cycling for professional and work purposes (dark blue line) remains among the lowest levels, signalling that cycling for work purposes is not a popular choice in the Netherlands, especially considering the increase in remote work. Overall, the graph shows that the pandemic temporarily affected some categories of cycling, but the recovery was rapid, particularly for leisure and shopping purposes.

4. Emission Analysis

The implementation of Euro emissions standards has played a crucial role in the reduction of the CO2 emissions of vehicles in Europe. This had huge contribution in improving the air quality and fighting climate change. These standards have been introduced in 1992 with Euro 1. These standards regulated the emissions of new vehicles, and they have become more and more stringent in each subsequent version. In 1996, Euro 2 has been introduced and it reduced the limits for carbon monoxide and the combined limit for unburned hydrocarbons and nitrogen oxide, as well as introducing different levels for petrol and diesel engines. Euro 3, implemented in 2000, and Euro 4 in 2005, brought significant advancement in emission reduction technologies. Later, Euro 5 in 2009 and Euro 6 in 2014 have introduced stricter regulations that emphasized the fuel efficieny and has promoted the adoption of particulate filters and catalytic converters to reduce the harmful emissions, including CO2. The constant tightening of these standards, combined with the advancement in technology and the widespread of EVs has contributed to a gradual decline in CO2 emissions from the automotive sector. (Euro 1 to Euro 6 Vehicle Emissions Standards | RAC Drive, n.d.)

The plot shows CO2 emissions by transport type over time. In particular, the transport types analyzed are Passenger cars, Motorcycles, vehicles with moped licenses, Light-weight commercial motor vehicles, Heavy-weight commercial motor vehicles, and Buses. The general trend that is possible to analyze is that the highest CO2 emissions are observed in passenger cars, followed by light-weight and heavy-weight, buses, and motorcycles. The total emissions of CO2 show an increase from 1990 until around 2005. However, after that, they started to stabilize. Furthermore, around 2020 there was a noticeable dip which is attributed to the decrease in transportation activities related to the Covid 19. The stricter regulations may have reduced the emissions of a single new vehicle, there are still a significant amount of old vehicles on Dutch roads. The percentage of older vehicles in increasing year over year, explaining the gradual impact of the Euro emissions standards (https://www.cbs.nl/en-gb/figures/detail/82044eng). So, to conclude there are two main changes the post-2005 decline and the pandemic-related sharp decline in 2020.

The graph above shows normalized emission levels for some of the most relevant pollutants. A normalized plot is used as the difference in total emissions by weight varies a lot by pollutant. gives insights into the trends of four different pollutants: CO2, N2O, methane (CH4), and NOx from 1990 to 2023.

The carbon dioxide (CO2) is possible to identify with the blue line. Its trend starts low in the 1990s and steadily rises until 2004, where it reaches a peak. After this, the CO2 emissions gradually decline, with a significant dip around 2020 due to COVID-19, followed by a rebound. The decline coincides with the implementation of Euro 4, which drastically tightens the limit of emissions.

The nitrous oxide (N20) is identified with the red dashed line, and it shows a concerning increase trend. Interesting also to see how the N2O is only partially impacted by COVID. Furthermore, there are no Euro standards that directly want to address this problem, which is also the reason why it keeps increasing; however, it is important to implement policies to lower it since its global warming potential is concerning.

The methane (CH4) is indicated with the green line; the trend shows a steep decline from the early 1990s until almost zero by 2020. The Euro standards have become more and more stringent; this has led to improved fuel injection and combustion technologies, which have helped the reduction of methane emissions. Its reduction is a very good sign; however, the maintenance of its low level is essential.

Nitrogen Oxides (Nox) are shown in the graph with the yellow dotted line; it has a similar trend to the methane; declining consistently over time. The Euro 3 and Euro 4 have been essential years to tighten the limits, particularly for the diesel vehicles. The Nox limits implemented with Euro 3 for diesel were 0.50 g/km, while for petrol they were 0.15 g/km, and with the implementation of Euro 4, these have been even more restricted. This limit has been decreased until the Euro 6, when they have become 0.18 g/km for diesel and 0.06 g/km for petrol.

The different trends among pollutants show how the control of emissions is very complicated, and even if the regulatory measures and technological advancements have reduced CH4 NOx and CO2 +, N2O reduction remain a challenge. However, this is essential in the reduction of the overall environmental and climate impact of transportation emissions.

4.1 Year-over-year percentage change in CO Emissions

The graph illustrates the year-over-year change in carbon dioxide (CO) emissions from 1990 to 2020. The bar chart provides a clear view of how the level of emissions fluctuates, this helps to identify significant deviations over time. In the visualisation, the bars are all grey, this indicates that all the changes in emissions are quite regular. However, there is a standout red bar in 2020, this highlights a substantial decline due to the global impact of the COVID-19 pandemic. This sharp drop is caused by the lockdowns, which have reduced transportation and industrial activities. On the other hand, there is a small bounce back after 2020 due to the restart of many commercial activities. Furthermore, it is possible to notice how the changes from 2000 have been lower compared to the previous year, indicating that we are in the right direction. However, the inversion of trend should be reached. An interesting conclusion that can be extrapolated by this graph is that societal behaviour can rapidly change the emission level; however, this can happen on the negative or positive.

4.2 CO Emissions with Pre- and Post-2020 Trends

This graph shows the CO2 emission levels over time. It is divided into the period before 2020 and after it. The reason behind this split is caused by the COVID-19 pandemic; indeed, this allows for a comparison of patterns before and after this disruptive event. In this chart, the data points pre-2020 are represented by blue dots, and they show an overall increase reflecting global industrialisation, economic growth, and a rising demand for transportation. This highlights an ongoing challenge in curbing emissions despite advancements in emission reduction technology and policy. However, important to notice is that the graph from 2010 has started to have smaller fluctuations, and the overall breadth of the graph is starting to reduce, indicating a small and small increase year by year of emissions. Post 2020, the yellow dots and yellow dashed trend line show a different story. Indeed, following the sharp decline in 2020 due to COVID-19, there is a noticeable rebound. This indicates a "recovery" in emissions since economic and transportation activities have completely returned to operation worldwide. To conclude, there is an interesting trend of reduction of the breadth of the fluctuation of CO emission levels over time; however, there are outliers data due to the COVID pandemic, so it is needed to see how the situation will evolve after the complete rebound after the COVID situation and whether the breadth of the fluctuations and the overall emissions levels keep decreasing. With the implementation of stricter guidelines in the coming years and prevalence of low- and zero-emission zones in city centers, a decline in all pollutants is expected.

5. Conclusion

This document was drafted with the aim of measuring the impact of a country's green policies, particularly in the transportation sector. The Netherlands is used as a virtuous example of a country that has initiated a decarbonization process. The report explores how the government promotes the use of zero-emission transportation, such as bicycles and electric vehicles (EVs). This allows us to recognize that the widespread adoption of these means of transport is not due to external events, but to policies with long-term effects.

The first topic, concerning EVs, highlights how the market has been growing since incentives were allocated in 2020. Investments in infrastructure and urban innovation are also notable, with municipalities providing bicycle lanes, thereby facilitating cycling as a mode of transport.

The second point in the document explains how bicycle use has become universal within Dutch society. This is evident from the charts on usage habits, as well as those showing the average distance traveled per year. Such statistics would not be possible without cities organized and designed around this mode of transport.

The third part of the report illustrates the current trends in pollutant emissions, with a focus on CO, the primary metric in transportation-related emissions. This section also covers the COVID-19 period, a unique moment in the history of pollution data collection. Special graphs were created to account for this impact. The theme of the pandemic is recurring, with references in sections 1 and 2: in the first, it marks a clear turning point, and in the second, it highlights the sharp decrease in the use of various transport modes.

In conclusion, the direction taken by the European Union and the Netherlands is clear and well-defined. Nonetheless, pollutant emissions remain too high for us to be assured of a future without climate repercussions. The Netherlands serves as a model and benchmark among European countries. What must be further improved is the transition from combustion vehicles to EVs. While bicycles offer an excellent solution, implementing such a solution in the short term may prove challenging in other countries lacking suitable infrastructure.
